== Pronunciation ==
\Pre*cau"tion\,
== Etimology==

[[F.]] ''pr['e]cation'', [[L.]] ''praecautio'', [[fr.]] ''praecavere'', ''praecautum'', to guard against beforehand; ''prae'' (before) + ''cavere'' (be on one's guard).  See [[Pre-]], and [[Caution]]].

=== Noun ===
1. Previous caution or care; caution previously employed to prevent mischief or secure good; as, his life was saved by precaution.

 They [[ancient]] [[philosopher]]s treasured up their supposed discoveries with miserable precaution. --J. H. Newman.

2. A measure taken beforehand to ward off evil or secure good or success; a precautionary act; as, to take precautions against accident.

=== Verb===

==== Transitive ====

[[Cf.]] [[F.]] ''pr['e]cautionner''

1. To warn or caution beforehand. --[[w:Locke|Locke]].

2. To take precaution against. [R.] --Dryden.

